article.description:
Kelly Schumacher helped put Indiana into the WNBA playoffs, scoring a career-high 15 points in her first start
of the season as the Fever beat the Cleveland Rockers 60-56 on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Backup center helps Fever reach playoffs
article.linkText: Playoff Fever: Schumacher's career night lifts Indiana
article.story:
CLEVELAND (AP) -- Kelly Schumacher helped put Indiana into the
WNBA playoffs, scoring a career-high 15 points as the Fever beat
the Cleveland Rockers 60-56 on Tuesday night.

	   "I was really excited,'' said Schumacher, who made her first
start of the season at center when Olympia Scott-Richardson was
placed on the injured list before the regular-season finale because
of a sore right foot.

	   Fever guard Nikki McCray, who chanted "Kelly! Kelly'' in the
locker room, missed the final 14 minutes because of a dislocated
finger on her right hand, but said she will try to play in the
playoff opener against New York.

	   "I cannot even begin to describe this,'' coach Nell Fortner
said after Indiana capped an improbable run to the playoffs with
its sixth victory in seven games. "It is phenomenal. I'm so proud
of this team.''

	   Indiana and Orlando finished the season 16-16, but the Fever
took the fourth and final Eastern Conference playoff spot with a
2-1 edge over the Miracle in the season series.

	   Schumacher, who also had a career-best nine rebounds, dominated
the final two minutes as the Fever (16-16) earned the first playoff
berth in their three-year history. Indiana tied for the league's
worst record last season at 10-22.

	   "I was really concentrating on defense and let everything else
just happen,'' Schumacher said. "We had to keep them from
scoring.''

	   With the score tied at 56, Schumacher blocked a shot by
Cleveland's Chasity Melvin. Seconds later, the 6-foot-4 center
scored on a layup for a 58-56 lead with 1:21 to play.

	   Schumacher grabbed a loose ball on Cleveland's next possession,
but Indiana turned the ball over.

	   The Rockers' Penny Taylor then missed a 3-point shot with 16
seconds to play, and Indiana's Coquese Washington made two free
throws with 13 seconds left to make it 60-56.

	   "We were right there and gave them a scare,'' Taylor said.
"You have to make big shots and unfortunately I didn't make that
one.''

	   Taylor led Cleveland with 22 points and 10 rebounds. She scored
14 points and Ann Wauters had 10 in the first half to spark
Cleveland to a 37-27 lead at the break. Indiana had been 3-11 when
trailing at the half.

	   Washington scored 12 of her 14 points in the first half. Indiana
is 8-3 since acquiring her from Houston in July.

	   Fever rookie star Tamika Catchings, the only player in the
league who leads her team in scoring, rebounding and assists, shot
0-for-7 in the first half. She finished with nine points on
3-for-15 shooting.

	   "My teammates picked up the slack,'' said Catchings, who hit
her first shot 20 seconds into the second half.

	   Catchings drove to the basket to tie the score at 51 with 8:39
to play, then hit a 3-pointer with 6:57 left to give the Fever
their first lead at 54-51.

	   "One of the things we talked about at halftime was making a run
to the playoffs,'' Catchings said. "In order to do that, we had to
play better defense and chip away on offense.

	   The Rockers (10-22) lost their final six games and nine of their
last 11. Cleveland, which went 14-2 at home last year and won the
Eastern Conference, finished with the second-worst record in
franchise history and lost its final nine home games. The Rockers
were 7-25 in 1999. Cleveland lost seven home games in which it had
double-digit leads.

	   "It is baffling as to why that happened,'' Taylor said. "We
just have to put this year behind us and get ready for next year.''
